<DOC><DOCNO> AP900403-0194 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-03-90 0507EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-DigestBriefs     04-03 0506</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Digest Briefs,0526</SECOND><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Seeking to ease rising tensions, PresidentVytautas Landsbergis of Lithuania has struck a conciliatory chordby saying his republic intends to move toward independencegradually and through negotiations.   Landsbergis told Lithuanian lawmakers on Monday that their March11 declaration of independence ``may seem to some people ... ademand that power be handed over the very next day. ''   ``We did not expect this and did not count upon it,'' he said,retreating somewhat from the recalcitrance that had characterizedthe Baltic state's drive for divorce from the Soviet Union.   Landsbergis said his republic intended to ``consolidate'' itsindependence ``by means of agreements and a gradual takeover ofcertain functions.''</TEXT><DATELINE>PONCA CITY, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Conoco Inc., in one of the biggestsettlements of its kind, has agreed to pay $23 million to buy 400homes and compensate families who say its refinery is giving themcancer and other illnesses.   Under the settlement announced Monday with families who had suedthe company for allegedly contaminating the air and water, Conocowould buy the properties for about $18 million and establish a $5million compensation fund.   Homeowner Mike Gallagher said his family was ready to move.   ``The sooner, the better. Now we can go to the other side oftown. No more nosebleeds. No more headaches. We can live withgood-smelling air,'' he said.</TEXT><DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The runoff campaign between two Democratsvying for governor began with talk of a peace treaty. But thatdidn't last long.   Heading into the April 10 election, Treasurer Ann Richards andAttorney General Jim Mattox have attacked each other on personalfinances and drug use, with only a gaffe by the Republicancandidate to remind them of their common foe.   The two cannot even agree on when to disagree in a debate.   ``If Ann Richards is not tough enough to stand up and debate JimMattox and to answer the questions that are on the voters' minds,how is she going to be tough enough to stand up to the problemsfacing our state?'' demanded Mattox, who has accused Ms. Richardsof refusing to debate him to avoid questions about drugs.</TEXT><DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Greeks will vote again Sunday, for thethird time in a year, in hopes of breaking a political deadlockthat has created compromise governments unable to confront aneconomy in crisis and growing terrorism.   Pollsters predict the election will end like those in June andNovember 1989, with no party winning enough seats to control thegovernment.   Coalitions formed after last year's elections took no effectiveaction on foreign, domestic or economic policy. The EuropeanCommunity has said Greece is in danger of bankruptcy and the ECwill not bail it out because Greece violated austerity requirementsof a 1985 loan.   Some Greek officials and economists fear the nation may have tosurrender some of its economic sovereignty and seek help for thefirst time from the International Monetary Fund.</TEXT></DOC>